  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2566046632" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2566046632" />
    <a title="Malcolm" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5860800-malcolm"><img alt="Malcolm" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1386870354p2/5860800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2566046632?book_show_action=true">Oct 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Malcolm" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Malcolm" href="/user/show/5860800-malcolm">Malcolm</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007212279" href="/book/show/579379.Four_Souls">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5860800-malcolm?shelf=fiction-contemporary">fiction-contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5860800-malcolm?shelf=first-nations">first-nations</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5860800-malcolm?shelf=lit-like">lit-like</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2566046632" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10382744700467619008">Louise Erdrich’s elegant, mellifluous prose seduces us into her Ojibway world peopled by those we’ve come to know well over the years. At the heart of this small tale of revenge and of the unintended consequences of seeking to recover lost land, land the family has been cheated out of, is Fleur Pillager, who we’ve met before in Erdrich’s novels.<br/><br/>As the last living member of a family whose land was acquired by a lumber robber baron in the early years of the 20th century, Fleur – who becomes Four S</span>
  <span id="freeText10382744700467619008" style="display:none">Louise Erdrich’s elegant, mellifluous prose seduces us into her Ojibway world peopled by those we’ve come to know well over the years. At the heart of this small tale of revenge and of the unintended consequences of seeking to recover lost land, land the family has been cheated out of, is Fleur Pillager, who we’ve met before in Erdrich’s novels.<br /><br />As the last living member of a family whose land was acquired by a lumber robber baron in the early years of the 20th century, Fleur – who becomes Four Souls – heads out to Minneapolis-St Paul to seek revenge in his death. Things don’t quite go as planned – and the intention to kill becomes the actuality of marriage, although his death remains a possibility: it would achieve the goal when the husband’s property becomes the wife’s, but the killing has to be more cunning, and Fleur can’t quite bring herself to dispose to John James Mauser. As is the case with so much of Erdrich’s work, unintended outcomes reshape the lives of the characters. <br /><br />As is also the case with much of Erdrich’s work the narrative shifts around, spiralling in on itself and on its wider circumstances – we’ve met many of the characters before, or have heard of them, and others from other novels are mentioned, not that knowledge of those novels is necessary to get into this one. Much of the spiral form turns on the presence of three narrators – Nanapush, Fleur’s adopted father; Polly Elizabeth Gheen, Mauser’s former sister-in-law who moves back to the Mauser household when Fleur becomes pregnant; and Margaret Kashpaw, Nanapush’s wife who appears as a character from the outset but only as a narrator in the last third of the story. <br /><br />Reservation life centres on Nanapush &amp; Margaret’s marriage, city life on Fleur &amp; Mauser’s. Both of these relationships become microcosmic sites of settler and indigenous ways where, in their very particularity, they become tales of a much wider historical relationship and the incompatibility of settler colonial relations. Not that these are simplistic, two dimensional tropes: Mauser seems to feel guilt over his exploitation and seems to relish the thought of death a Fleur’s hand, while Margaret may have one foot in the camp of the old ways, able to reconcile that her Catholicism, but that still doesn’t stop her yearning for the material acquisitions the colonisers bring – leading to some of Nanapush’s most absurd moments. <br /><br />One of the great aspects of Erdrich’s writing is beautiful and seductively smooth flowing as it is, it never impedes the flow of the story, and while it may not be clear where this narrative is taking us, we’re always sure it is taking us somewhere. What’s more, that somewhere is not a narrative-driven outcome but the product of the interaction of characters and their shifting, developing, growing relations. Watching these relations and relationships become things new is one of the delights of Erdrich’s work in amongst these families, perhaps in part because even if we’ve not read them these characters have form, have relations, have history, have ways of being in Erdrich’s world conjured in other novels in a way that gives them a presence that doesn’t happen with the same depth in her stand-alone novels. <br /><br />Expect to laugh, expect the occasional tear to well up, expect disbelief (Nanapush’s recurrent jealousy is a fine source of humour and cringe-worthiness) and expect a sense of satisfaction at who is on the receiving end of comeuppance, and how it comes to be. Expect also to be reminded that the paths to healing are often not the most direct, and often the least expected.<br /><br />Whenever I read her work, I am surprised the Erdrich is not more well-known; this divine novel is evidence of why she should be.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10382744700467619008" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


